          <h2>Celestial Navigation Using Constellations</h2>
          <p>For thousands of years, constellations served as the primary navigation system for travelers, sailors, and nomads. While modern GPS has largely replaced celestial navigation, understanding how to use star patterns remains a valuable survival skill and deepens appreciation of the night sky.</p>

          <h3>Finding Direction</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Finding North:</strong> Follow the pointer stars of the Big Dipper (Merak and Dubhe) about five times their separation distance to reach Polaris, which marks true north to within 1°</li>
            <li><strong>Finding South:</strong> The long axis of the Southern Cross points toward the south celestial pole. Extend a line from the cross's top star (Gacrux) through its bottom star (Acrux) about 4.5 times the cross's length</li>
            <li><strong>East-West Orientation:</strong> All stars rise in the east and set in the west (except circumpolar stars). Orion rises almost due east and sets due west, making it an excellent east-west marker</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Determining Latitude</h3>
          <p>In the northern hemisphere, your latitude approximately equals Polaris's altitude above the horizon. At the equator (0° latitude), Polaris sits on the horizon. At the North Pole (90° latitude), it's directly overhead. This relationship made Polaris invaluable for historical maritime navigation.</p>

          <h3>Telling Time</h3>
          <p>Circumpolar constellations rotate around the pole once every 23 hours 56 minutes (one sidereal day). The Big Dipper's position relative to Polaris can be used like a 24-hour clock hand, rotating counterclockwise in the northern hemisphere. With practice and tables, navigators could determine the time to within 15-30 minutes.</p>
