          </ul>

          <h3>Best Observing Conditions</h3>
          <p>New moon periods provide the darkest skies for learning constellations. Light pollution significantly affects visibility—from a dark sky site, you might see 8-9 magnitude stars, revealing intricate constellation patterns. From light-polluted cities, you may only see magnitude 3-4 stars, making patterns harder to discern. However, even from cities, the brightest stars of major constellations remain visible.</p>
